segments.text: change the cadence right when you were passing the reviewing stand and that they would do that just to mess you up but i know they didn't do that for us because we were always close to the bottom on our marching ability so what about intramurals was that highly competitive highly competitive and uh uh
for you know sort of I guess random chance we had a lot of high school athletes in my freshman unit and did very well in intramurals and after that I'm you know I remember you always
You always fielded a team even if you were told at 3 o'clock on Tuesday afternoon that you were going to go over and pitch horseshoes for the unit or something.
You would dutifully go do it.
What was your favorite and least favorite intramural activities?
Well, I don't remember.

because of my uh because of the many good athletes in our freshman unit I didn't get to participate on a lot of the you know more glamorous the flag football or the basketball or things like that um so I'm trying to think of some of the things that I did um uh
I remember being, representing our unit in tennis and maybe some of the minor things.
There was bowling.
You know, there were a lot of things that, but I don't remember that I was particularly good enough to do any of those things.
Were there any intramural sports that were very new to you?
Like they didn't do rugby, did they?
No.
And lacrosse.
No, none of those things.
I think that pretty much everything that we did was something that didn't seem like a rare or unusual sport.
You said you were an RV.
Describe how the process, as far as you understand it, how a person became a RV selectee.
Well, in those days you had to apply.
And that started in your sophomore year.
And you, they would go through the,
then you had to interview and you had to you know get yourself all polished and shined up you know and on your best military bearing and everything and they would interview you and then they
forgotten whether we got a letter or whether we just we got a list sort of.
Do you remember anything about the interview?
What was the topic?
What were the topics of the?
I don't remember anything about.
Were these all RV members doing the interviewing or were there some core advisors?
There was probably a core advisor present but all of the questioning was done by the
membership committee and so you could get in, it seems like there were two stages that you could get into the RVs, but I may be remembering, that's probably Alpha Zeta.
You could get in as a sophomore or as a junior.
So in the RVs, at the end of your sophomore year, you either were in or out.
Do you have any idea how many were selected, how many new members each year?
I have the impression that there were about 100 or 120 in the unit or something like that and half of them had to be new each year.
As far as you're aware, then and now, was the selection fair?
I really don't remember anybody that applied and didn't make it.
in those days.
But it was pretty well known that you had, I don't remember what it was, but there was a minimum GPA and there were

you had to have something, some kind of leadership activity, and you had to have done something in the Corps, and the reason that I chose to do it was sort of personal discipline, not so much, you know, I didn't want to go to New Orleans and march in whatever parade that was,
than run amok on Bourbon Street, which some of the guys, you know, that's really what they wanted to do.
But I thought that it was about the highest challenge as far as drill and ceremonies here.
And I thought I was not good in drill and ceremonies or marching or anything.
And I needed to be better at that.
And so that's the reason.
Was there any kind of formal initiation
Yes, they had an initiation banquet and we had to show up in our white suits.
Did you have to buy those?
Yes.
Well, I think so.
At least part of it, we may have.
We certainly had to buy the hats and things like that.
And the uniform then is exactly the same uniform, isn't it, in design and color?
I think so.
It was a white uniform and wore black shoes.
What were some of the important events that you participated in as an RV?
Well, I had some kind of a conflict with the New Orleans trip and I didn't make that.
But we did go to San Antonio to the Battle of the Flowers and marched there.
And then I was not active as a senior.
Most of the juniors that came in every year did not stay on as seniors.
So if you weren't an officer, it was,
it was optional and to, you know, whether or not you were gonna be active as a senior, so.
So did you march in the inaugural parade?
No, I don't remember there being an inauguration while I was.
And were there any important visitors to the campus that you remember being a?
No.
A guard for them?
No, I don't.
I remember that we, that the RVs had something to do at Mother's Day or, and probably at final review.
But I know on Mother's Day we had to put on a drill.
And I remember that.
Did, what'd you do with your uniform when,
Did you keep it, sell it, give it away?
I don't remember.
I don't think.
I may have some of the epaulets or other additions to that uniform, but I don't have the uniform.
And I don't remember what I did with it.
Were you aware as a student that there were any secret fraternities here?
There was a rumor that there were some and I think that during my student years there was a scandal and some people were dismissed.
I never did understand much about that.
I didn't really know anything about it beforehand and was sort of appalled when it all came out.
The details never did really come out.
I mean, it would be things in the battalion that so many students were put on probation or dismissed or something.
Did you and your buddies read the PAT during that era?
Yes, I think so.
Did you all give high credibility to the battalion?
I don't remember that ever being discussed very much.
I think the battalion was probably always struggling.
Student newspapers were always struggling to be as straightforward as the editors wanted to be, and the administration was always trying to suppress them, and at least that was there.
their arguments.
How often did your special lady come to visit the campus?
I cannot remember her coming down here over once or twice and she,
And then the one year she met me in Austin and went to the football game there.
But she was, her background was about the same as mine and so it was not, it's not particularly easy for her to travel.
I guess she came down my sophomore year for a football game here.
And where would she have stayed?
She stayed with some people that I had met at the Central Baptist Church.
And I kind of forgot that.
But that's right.
I went there some and had met some people and she stayed with them.
And there were some faculty families that lived over,
south of Guyon Hall, weren't there still?
Yes.
And students, guests stayed with them sometimes, didn't they?
Yes.
Did you go to the boot dance and things like that?
I didn't do that, and when I graduated,

we were planning to get married and we were focusing mostly on uh finishing up here and getting away so she didn't come down let's let's back up uh your junior year uh you bought some senior boots i presume yes from whom and how much do you remember well i bought them from somebody in the unit
and mostly based on their appearance and not on the fact that they fit me.
I remember they were about two sizes too big or something like that, but they were okay.
And I don't remember much about what the price was, but it seems like, you know, that it was around $100 or maybe a little more than that.
You were spending money on that.
You still had the 41 Chevy.
Yes, at that time, yes.
You went to the movie occasionally and you ate out occasionally.
Any other personal expenses where you spent money for a good time?
I can't really remember.
We, you know, we would do things like,
Play basketball or play tennis or something like that as recreation.
On campus.
On campus.
Uh-huh.
What were the student indulgences of the, what were people smoking?
If you're talking about drugs, I never heard of anyone using any kind of drugs during that time.
Had you even heard the words?
I don't remember ever hearing anyone that said, you know, they even knew someone that did it.
I don't remember ever hearing it discussed.
The indulgences, I guess, the only one that I knew about was alcohol.
And people drank, was it beer or whiskey where they were drinking much?

I don't I guess it was I don't guess I really know but you know this county was dry and so people people that drank would maybe go out across the river into Burleson County and get something and bring it back and show up at the dorm at two o'clock in the morning roaring drunk and
throwing coke bottles down the hall and this sort of thing.
But that's, that was a minor, that was a very obvious minority of the student body.
And the smokers were smoking cigarettes.
Yeah, and a lot of people would smoke cigars on,
a Yale practice night so they could blow the smoke in some poor freshman's face and not smoke any other time.
And I don't remember, you know, I don't remember many people smoking, but I guess there were a lot.
And did any of them smoke pipes?
A few, yeah.
Did people smoke in the dorms?
Yes.
Because there wasn't any rule against it, were there?
Not that I know of.
Telephones.
If you needed to make a telephone call, where was the telephone available to a dorm student?
Usually there was a pay phone in the lounge.
And, of course, they required cash.
They were not, you know, there was no such thing as a credit card operated phone in those days.
and people didn't have enough quarters.

you know to make a long distance call usually so they would go over to the MSC and there was this room that I described a minute ago that was um well if you go down the steps past the registration desk for the room registration area there it was just on the left there and I guess it it's had several uses since that time and there was an operator there
and a bunch of phones and you could pay cash there and make a phone call.
You'd go up after you finished your call and she would tell you what your charges were.
And then your senior ring, do you remember what it cost?
No, I don't.
I remember that it was subsidized.
It may have been less than $50 though.
And how did you feel when you put that ring on?
Well, that was a great feeling, you know.
I don't, I don't,
I don't remember feeling like I would never get it, you know, but I just was very happy to have it.
And everybody that I knew, you know, smiled at me and said, you know, that your right hand has suddenly gotten to where you can't keep it anywhere except more or less straight out in front of you.
And the ring was far more
personally important than the boots, wasn't it?
Yes.
Yes.
And it was more important than the diploma, you know.
I mean, it was the thing that people would see when you'd be anywhere else.
And it was the thing that was going to be a symbol of recognition the rest of your life.
Do you have any good ring stories to share?
where somebody saw one, saw it a zillion miles away?
Oh, all over the world, you know.
I mean, I've had people come up to me on an airplane in Europe, you know, and say, I saw your ring and, you know, in Japan and in Brazil.

just in the most unlikely places that I've ever been an Aggie will turn up and say I saw your ring and you then suddenly realize that he has one on too the airplane in Europe the two people that had on Aggie rings were coeds

after the time that women were here and women were graduating and wearing rings and we were flying from England someplace and there were two young women wearing Aggie rings that saw mine and whipped out.
So that was a pretty amazing experience.
Have you ever lost yours?
No.
Okay, so you don't have a story there.
No.
Let's see, then as you're getting ready for commencement, you still think you're going to be a professional in ranching, in agriculture.
And you got your commission and you think you're going to get called to active duty, is that right?
Yes.
But the Korean War is over.
Right.
How did you and your buddies feel about the fact that the war was over?

Well I know that everybody was glad because it had it had stalemated no one thought we were going to settle it militarily and so the longer it lasted the more useless deaths were going to occur and so everybody was glad that it was over

And it really had an impact on the Army because the Army was funneling these second lieutenants through and sending them to Korea and they were, you know, they were not lasting very long over there in combat.
And all of a sudden there was no need for this cannon fodder so they had to cut back on, they had to change the way they handled the ROTC graduates.
they didn't have places to put all these second lieutenants in the peacetime army now.

So that was the reason that I was, my orders were changed and I went in for six months training and I had worked for the soil conservation service for a while after I graduated and decided I didn't want to do that any longer.
And so that's when I decided that I was going to go to graduate school.
And I came back here to A&M still not sure what I was going to do.

My, one of my college roommates and I had been on active duty for training at the same time and we were talking about geology and changing our majors, you know, and starting all over and he actually started down that trail and didn't finish.
And I decided that I was going to go into research.
So that's how I actually came to meet Wayne Hall.
Yeah, we want to get to that in a minute.
Yeah.
So I started back to A&M exactly one year and one summer semester after I graduated.
I was back here on campus enrolled in graduate school.
working in range management with my major professor's name was Robert Darrow.
D-A-R-R-O-W?
D-A-R-R-O-W, yes.
And Wayne McCully was one of his PhD students, and he was sort of my day-to-day advisor.
And so we started back here.
By that, I'd been married a little over a year at that time.
My wife went to work for the City National Bank within two weeks of when we arrived here.
And so that was the beginning of my graduate experience.
Let's back up and do some of the senior traditions.
Final review, did you go through final review?
Yes.
What did it feel like?

it as a junior it's a great experience you know because you're you know you just almost feel like you could change your clothes in the front of the whole world just to get to wear those boots you know and I remember running off to find a dorm someplace to change and put on my boots and everything and

and uh I was company commander and so you know that was the first time I was going to be out in front of the company and lead them past through using Stan and everything we practiced that some ahead of time and uh so that was that was a good experience uh I think
My wife-to-be was present for that final review.
This your junior year?
Junior year.
Yeah.
Yeah.
And then my senior year, you know, everybody said, well, it'll be, you just won't be able to stand it, you know, you'll be so sad and everything.
Well, I was ready to graduate, you know.
I mean, being a student had been a lot of fun and being in the Corps,
in the end was fun.
You know, I didn't have a lot of fun my freshman and sophomore year, but I didn't come, you know, to have fun.
I came to survive and to graduate.
And so, but I was ready to go on with my life at that point.
And I was not all teary-eyed about, you know, not going to be here for bonfire next year and all that sort of stuff.
Alright, then commencement, where was commencement held your senior year?
G. Raleigh or Guyon, or do you remember?
Well, it had to be G. Raleigh.
And did family come?
I don't, I don't believe they did.
I don't remember now.
But every name was called, every handshake.
Yes.
As you were getting ready to leave the campus then, how well prepared did you feel A&M had made you?
What did you think you had learned?
Well, I had mixed feelings.
I guess that I didn't
have any reservations about my ability to do the you know whatever jobs that I might get
I was not at that point very confident that I was prepared to do what I wanted to do.
I wasn't sure I'd made the right decisions about my future.
And so I was still very much in doubt as to whether, you know, I wanted to go ahead and use my BS degree and rely on it for the rest of my life.
And that was then borne out in my first work experience where I saw what I thought was a very limited opportunity for advancement.
And I felt that just chilling that, you know, that you could spend the rest of your life doing something that approached sort of technical clerk and never advance any or very little.
And you had done well academically.
Overall head drill.
Yes.

And but this was a government bureaucracy and I just found that that mentality of that group was that they put you in a job more or less equivalent to a low level school teacher and that you'd be there the rest of your life and that you'd get a few little grade changes and that you'd
be happy to, you know, to have them.
You come back then a year, a little more than a year later, and you start out in what program?
Well, it was in the same department that I had graduated from.
And how did you get over to associate with this man named Wayne Hall?
Well, Robert Darrow was an interesting fellow.
He had come to A&M from the University of Arizona

and he had the reason that the story was that he had been involved in a competition for the selection of a new president and so he had supported one guy and the other guy had been selected and so then he decided that he was going to leave there and come to A&M and
So he worked in the area of what the ranchers called brush control, killing woody plants with chemicals.
And so he stressed that people that worked in this area needed to have a good background in plant physiology.
So he wanted me to go over and take Wayne Hall's
plant physiology courses and there was several of them that Wayne taught and I was very captivated with that.
He'd been here a couple years?

Darryl had no no no Wayne Hall had been here only six or seven years at that time he'd come in very late 40s or early 50s something like that so this is 56 and he's you know very active very outgoing type of person he's obviously
successful professionally.
Were you and other students aware of his status, of his credibility as a scholar when you took those courses?
Well the first course, no.
But the second course was on plant hormones and growth regulators and he brought
some of his research into those courses and that was of interest to me and he had several graduate students and I got to know all of them as a TA and pretty soon
I was pretty much aware of his scientific status and everything.
Make believe that I didn't know him at all.
Describe his personality and his manner of teaching.
Well, his nickname was Machine.
